      "skos:definition": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "Hybrid Dramaturgies designates a mode of artistic and epistemological practice in which heterogeneous layers of presence, mediation, materiality, recognition, temporality, inscription, and circulation are organized as an unstable, polysemic, and polyphonic structure of meaning. The concept applies to artworks, events, images, actions, devices, or systems in which signs, gestures, archives, images, repertoires, or structures of symbolic authority are reactivated within another regime of relation. What defines the operation is not the specific nature of the sign mobilized, but its density of recognition: its capacity to arrive already charged with memory, expectation, authority, circulation, or symbolic value."
      },
      "skos:scopeNote": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The concept has a transmedial, trans-support, and transcontextual scope. It applies to practices in which the work organizes a dramaturgy of layers: a tension among heterogeneous elements that operate together without merging into a stable unity. These layers may be bodily, technical, material, symbolic, discursive, infrastructural, exhibitionary, curatorial, documentary, social, or algorithmic. The concept does not apply to any multimedia work merely because it combines media, nor to any open, ambiguous, or polysemic work in a generic sense. The minimum condition is that the relation among layers produces a dramaturgical structure of meaning."
      },
      "skos:historyNote": {
        "@language": "en",
        "@value": "The concept is situated at the intersection of artistic research, practice as research, poietic epistemology of the image, semiotics, hermeneutics, performance studies, critical reenactment, postdramatic dramaturgy, the expanded field of the image, techno-aesthetics, and debates on circulation, infrastructure, and algorithmic regimes of visibility. Its specificity lies in displacing dramaturgy beyond theatre and dramatic text toward situations in which images, bodies, devices, archives, objects, discourses, infrastructures, and circuits of reception become simultaneous agents in the production of meaning."
      },
      "skos:note": [
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "SYNTHETIC FORMULATION: Hybrid Dramaturgies are artistic and epistemological structures in which heterogeneous layers of presence, mediation, recognition, materiality, inscription, and circulation enter into friction, reactivating signs or regimes of memory under new conditions of reading and producing polysemy, polyphony, symbolic displacement, and visual thought."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "HYBRIDITY: Hybridity, in this context, is not defined by the mere addition of media, supports, or languages. It designates the friction among layers that coexist without merging into a stable synthesis."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "POLYSEMY AND POLYPHONY: Polysemy does not correspond to an arbitrary multiplicity of interpretations, but to the organized production of simultaneous, related meanings that cannot be reduced to a single reading. Polyphony indicates that the work does not speak from a single voice: different regimes of enunciation — inherited sign, body, object, technique, archive, tradition, institution, critique, circulation, or documentation — coexist in tension. Ambiguity may emerge from this field, but it does not exhaust the operation."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "REACTIVATION: Hybrid Dramaturgies neither merely represent nor merely cite preexisting images. They critically reenact recognizable signs in order to reactivate their memory within another symbolic regime. The displaced sign becomes a field of friction between recognition and difference, reverence and irony, presence and mediation, cultural memory and contemporary circulation."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "SELF-IMPLICATION: Through the Self-Implicative Method, subsequent writing does not comment on the work from outside. It prolongs the dramaturgical operation, reinscribing it in critical language and expanding its public existence without reducing its polysemy, polyphony, or hermeneutic openness."
        },
        {
          "@language": "en",
          "@value": "SEMANTIC-WEB MODELING: For semantic-web use, Hybrid Dramaturgies should be modeled as a skos:Concept, schema:DefinedTerm, and crm:E28_Conceptual_Object. The concept should not be reduced to a medium-based category such as photography, performance, video, installation, archive, or digital art. Its defining feature is the articulation of multiple layers as a single epistemic-dramaturgical operation."
        }
      ],
